        "content": "<p>If I am interested in using a lemma, but am not sure if it is applicable, then one of things I'm encouraged to do is look up the signature / declaration / definition.</p>\n<p>For <code>le_or_lt</code> this is :</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"n\">le_or_lt</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">u_1</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">α</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">u_1</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">LinearOrder</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">α</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">b</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">α</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">≤</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">b</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∨</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">b</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">&lt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>I can't immediately tell from this that it is applicable to <code>Nat</code> or <code>Int</code> or <code>Real</code>. </p>\n<p>I am guess the variable type <code>α</code> must be a <code>LinearOrder</code> which in turn means naturals, integers, rationals and reals but not complex numbers.</p>\n<p>Is that correct?</p>",
        "id": 481348740,
        "sender_full_name": "rzeta0",
        "timestamp": 1731083651
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes. You can see in <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=LinearOrder#doc\">docs#LinearOrder</a> what instances of it are defined</p>",
        "id": 481351055,
        "sender_full_name": "Daniel Weber",
        "timestamp": 1731084487
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The relevant ones here are <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Nat.instLinearOrder#doc\">docs#Nat.instLinearOrder</a>, <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Int.instLinearOrder#doc\">docs#Int.instLinearOrder</a>, <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Rat.linearOrder#doc\">docs#Rat.linearOrder</a>, <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Real.linearOrder#doc\">docs#Real.linearOrder</a></p>",
        "id": 481351209,
        "sender_full_name": "Daniel Weber",
        "timestamp": 1731084550
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You can also run <code>#synth LinearOrder Nat</code> in the editor to see what lean finds</p>",
